	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I was driven to make a comment when I saw the statement saying that the 'complete' heals (they're not going to be complete heals -- read the info thoroughly.  They will have a cap around 2k hit points.  If you've ever played in the high end game, you know that warriors with 3500-5k hitpoints isn't uncommon.) are going to make clerics obsolete.  This isn't true in any fashion.<BR>
<BR>
Shaman are, primarily, a buffing class.  No one will deny this.  They can buff every single stat except WIS and INT.  That's pretty remarkable.  Not to mention Haste and Slow.  Doing these things is very mana intensive, and honestly their buffs are the focus of every shaman in a group setting.  <BR>
<BR>
Druids also fulfill some of that buffing role, but more than that they're snarers, rooters, evaccers and dotters.  But perhaps even more than Shaman they're considered excellent back-up healers.  <BR>
<BR>
Yes, they both have  back-up heals which are nice when the cleric is OOM or he's stunned or there's a mob on him and he can't cast,  but no group leader in their right mind would try camping any of the high-end zones (FG, Seb, Chardok, Akheva, Ssra etc etc) without a cleric,  CH-ing Shammy or druid notwithstanding.<BR>
<BR>
Plus, the cleric AC/HP buffs are unrivaled by any class anywhere.  Find me a better HP buff than Aegolism and I'll eat my own kidneys.<BR>
<BR>
Clerics will never be obsolete.  You're all just a jittery, paranoid  buncha lemmings.<BR>
<BR>
That being said... /sarcastic mode<BR>
<BR>
I'm soooo glad they're refining clerics even more when beastlords are such a rough sketch of a class, with so little definition!  *cheer*<BR>
<BR>
Xilsharn<BR>
53rd Beastlord of Cabilis<BR>
7th Hammer
